The Energy Department announced earlier on Thursday afternoon that from Wednesday consumers will have to cough up between 58 and 59 cents more for a litre of diesel. JOHANNESBURG - Economists say the latest fuel price hikes  were largely expected given the international increase in the price of crude oil. The petrol price is going up 49 cents a litre. The Energy Department announced earlier on Thursday afternoon that from Wednesday consumers will have to cough up between 58 and 59 cents more for a litre of diesel. Econometrix chief economist Azar Jammine says further hikes could be on the horizon. â€œThe prices have risen sharply in April and May. They will only be moderately higher in May compared with where they had been in December which was the last record-high level."